  					<td align=center valign="top" width=100%><br>
  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align='center' cellpadding=5 width='85%'>  <tr><td class='spti2' width='100%'>PLAYER STRATEGY - RANGER</td></tr>  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'><font class='dbti'>TRACKING</font> - <small>Anaxagoras, Povar</td></tr>
  <tr><td width='100%' class='db'>
<p>This is not so much as a guide to tracking for Rangers (though it might clear up some issues regarding tracking for them) as it is a description of what tracking is. Many people do not understand tracking, not just Rangers. This description applies to all classes that can track (Bards and Druids).<br>
<br>
Tracking is a skill that when used lists NPCs by name according to their spawn times (though times are not shown). NPCs at the top of the list are the most recent spawns, and the NPCs further down are less recent spawns. Tracking also gives you directional messages pointing you to the NPC when you have selected it in the tracking menu. E.g., you get messages like
'a Hill Giant is behind and to the left.' Unlike Sense the Dead, tracking doesn't point you automatically in the direction of the NPC.<br>
<br>
Tracking also lists PCs in the order that they entered the zone after you.<br>
<br>
Many Rangers have complained from time to time that they can be tracking an NPC only to find out that they could be standing next to an NPC that is not on tracking. For instance, someone Ranger is hunting and pulling in West Karana for Hill Giants. He gets a giant on tracking and starts to path towards it. On the way to the giant the Ranger passes another giant that was not on tracking. Some think this is a bug, but it is not. It is merely that the giant that was not on tracking is an old spawn that is no longer on the tracking list.<br>
<br>
Tracking also works in a radius from the Ranger in all directions. In a sense, tracking has a range that is a three dimensional sphere and any spawns in that sphere will show up on tracking. A Ranger can track things that are beneath him or above him, but this leads to some confusion at times. This range increases as the Ranger gains skill.<br>
<br>
Some Rangers complain that a Druid's or a Bard's tracking is better than theirs is because it doesn't confuse the tracker with spawns that are too far away. This is not true at all. A Ranger's tracking is the best there is and if you learn how to understand it you will see that in all cases where tracking is used, a Ranger excels at it without question.<br>
<br>
Some notable problems with tracking all revolve around locations of NPCs and PCs alike becoming confused to the tracking skill. At times you will be tracking an NPC in one direction when all of a sudden tracking reports it to be in a
totally different direction than where it previously was. I don't know the real reason for this but I think the problem has to do with the ghosting of NPCs and client side prediction. A similar, and often times much more annoying problem with
tracking is that in certain zones you can be tracking an PC (grouped or non grouped) and tracking just doesn't lead you anywhere near the person. You can be going straight towards the player and all of a sudden he is behind you, when you haven't passed him. I don't know why this happens, but my
guess is that it is also related to client side prediction. One final problem with tracking is that at times, in certain zones, it seems to have problems properly tracking NPCs/PCs that are at different elevations. Tracking notoriously sucks in West Karana in the hilly area, for instance, if the target is a roamer. Tracking never fails on static NPCs.<br>
<br>
Tracking is great for monitoring named spawns. It is also great for locating particular NPCs for your group to hunt. Tracking is a kind of radar letting the tracker know what is going on in his range of influence.<br>
<br>
Something that I have never yet been able to figure out is what determines the initial tracking list when you first zone into an area.<br>
<br>
Tracking can now be modified with 3 commands.<br>
<br>
1) /trackplayer off : turns off all PC listing on the tracking screen<br>
2) /trackplayer group : turns off all PC listing on the tracking screen, but not the people in your group<br>
3) /trackplayer all : turns on all tracking<br>
<br>
/trackplayer can be abbreviated to /tr<br>
<br>
Verant has mentioned that with Scars of Velious tracking will get an enhancement that will allow Rangers to track by the level of the NPC, and maybe also to filter out the list by level ranges.</p>
</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>&nbsp;</td></tr>
